# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: solenoids-relays
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A **contactor** is a type of relay (electrically operated switch) with high power rating (current rating and voltage rating).
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors usually refer to devices switching more than 15 amperes or in circuits rated more than a few kilowatts.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors are typically used to control electric motors (combination motor starters), lighting, heating, capacitor banks, thermal evaporators, and other electrical loads.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The physical size of contactors ranges from a device small enough to pick up with one hand, to large devices approximately a meter on a side.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors usually have provision for installation of additional contact blocks, rated for pilot duty, used in motor control circuits.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors have higher current, voltage and power ratings than other relays.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Thus, contactors are typically used for higher current or higher voltage switching; other relays are typically used for lower current or lower voltage switching.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Unlike other relays, contactors are designed to be directly connected to high-current load devices.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A contactor joins 2 poles together, without a common circuit between them.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Other relays may have a common contact that connects to a neutral position.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors are typically built for and used in three-phase applications; other relays are more commonly used in single-phase applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors generally have special structures for arc suppression to allow them to interrupt heavy currents, such as motor starting inrush current; other relays rely on other ways for arc suppression.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Coil voltages for contactors are often from 24 V AC/DC all the way up to 600 V AC; coil voltages for other relays are rarely high.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Other relays are usually designed for both *normally closed* and *normally open* applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Apart from optional auxiliary low-current contacts, contactors are almost exclusively fitted with normally open ("form A") contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Unlike a circuit breaker, a contactor is not intended to interrupt a short circuit current.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors range from those having a breaking current of several amperes to thousands of amperes and 24 V DC to many kilovolts, not high enough to safely interrupt a short circuit current.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Sometimes an economizer circuit is also installed to reduce the power required to keep a contactor closed; an auxiliary contact reduces coil current after the contactor closes.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A somewhat greater amount of power is required to initially close a contactor than is required to keep it closed.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Such a circuit can save a substantial amount of power and allow the energized coil to stay cooler.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Economizer circuits are nearly always applied on DC contactor coils and on large AC contactor coils.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A basic contactor will have a coil input (which may be driven by either an AC or DC supply depending on the contactor design).
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Universal coils (driven by AC as well as DC) are also available in the market today.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The coil may be energized at the same voltage as a motor the contactor is controlling, or may be separately controlled with a lower coil voltage better suited to control by programmable controllers and lower-voltage pilot devices.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Certain contactors have series coils connected in the motor circuit; these are used, for example, for automatic acceleration control, where the next stage of resistance is not cut out until the motor current has dropped.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] When current passes through the electromagnet, a magnetic field is produced, which attracts the moving core of the contactor.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The electromagnet coil draws more current initially, until its inductance increases when the metal core enters the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The moving contact is propelled by the moving core; the force developed by the electromagnet holds the moving and fixed contacts together.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] When the contactor coil is de-energized, gravity or a spring returns the electromagnet core to its initial position and opens the contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] For contactors energized with alternating current, a small part of the core is surrounded with a shading coil, which slightly delays the magnetic flux in the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The effect is to average out the alternating pull of the magnetic field and so prevent the core from buzzing at twice line frequency.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Because arcing and consequent damage occurs just as the contacts are opening or closing, contactors are designed to open and close very rapidly; there is often an internal tipping-point mechanism to ensure rapid action.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Rapid closing can, however, lead to increase contact bounce which causes additional unwanted open-close cycles.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] One solution is to have bifurcated contacts to minimize contact bounce; two contacts designed to close simultaneously, but bounce at different times so the circuit will not be briefly disconnected and cause an arc.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Another technique for improving the life of contactors is contact wipe; the contacts move past each other after initial contact in order to wipe off any contamination.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Without adequate contact protection, the occurrence of electric current arcing causes significant degradation of the contacts, which suffer significant damage.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] An electrical arc occurs between the two contact points (electrodes) when they transition from a closed to an open (break arc) or from an open to a closed (make arc).
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The break arc is typically more energetic and thus more destructive.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The heat developed by the resulting electrical arc is very high, ultimately causing the metal on the contact to migrate with the current.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The extremely high temperature of the arc (tens of thousands of degrees Celsius) cracks the surrounding gas molecules creating ozone, carbon monoxide, and other compounds.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The arc energy slowly destroys the contact metal, causing some material to escape into the air as fine particulate matter.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] This activity causes the material in the contacts to degrade over time, ultimately resulting in device failure.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] For example, a properly applied contactor will have a life span of 10,000 to 100,000 operations when run under power; which is significantly less than the mechanical (non-powered) life of the same device which can be in excess of 20 million operations.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Most motor control contactors at low voltages (600 volts and less) are air break contactors; air at atmospheric pressure surrounds the contacts and extinguishes the arc when interrupting the circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Modern medium-voltage AC motor controllers use vacuum contactors.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] High voltage AC contactors (greater than 1,000 volts) may use vacuum or an inert gas around the contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] High voltage DC contactors (greater than 600 V) still rely on air within specially designed arc-chutes to break the arc energy.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] High-voltage electric locomotives may be isolated from their overhead supply by roof-mounted circuit breakers actuated by compressed air; the same air supply may be used to "blow out" any arc that forms.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors are rated by designed load current per contact (pole), maximum fault withstand current, duty cycle, design life expectancy, voltage, and coil voltage.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A general purpose motor control contactor may be suitable for heavy starting duty on large motors; so-called "definite purpose" contactors are carefully adapted to such applications as air-conditioning compressor motor starting.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The current rating of the contactor depends on utilization category.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] NEMA contactors for low-voltage motors (less than 1,000 volts) are rated according to NEMA size, which gives a maximum continuous current rating and a rating by horsepower for attached induction motors.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] NEMA standard contactor sizes are designated 00, 0, 1, 2, 3 to 9.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The horsepower ratings are based on voltage and on typical induction motor characteristics and duty cycle as stated in NEMA standard ICS2.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Exceptional duty cycles or specialized motor types may require a different NEMA starter size than the nominal rating.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Manufacturer's literature is used to guide selection for non-motor loads, for example, incandescent lighting or power factor correction capacitors.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors for medium-voltage motors (greater than 1,000 volts) are rated by voltage and current capacity.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Auxiliary contacts of contactors are used in control circuits and are rated with NEMA contact ratings for the pilot circuit duty required.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Normally these contacts are not used in motor circuits.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The nomenclature is a letter followed by a three-digit number, the letter designates the current rating of the contacts and the current type (i.e., AC or DC) and the number designates the maximum voltage design values.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Contactors are often used to provide central control of large lighting installations, such as an office building or retail building.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] To reduce power consumption in the contactor coils, latching contactors are used, which have two operating coils.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] One coil, momentarily energized, closes the power circuit contacts, which are then mechanically held closed; the second coil opens the contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A magnetic starter is a device designed to provide power to electric motors.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] It includes a contactor as an essential component, while also providing power-cutoff, under-voltage, and overload protection.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Vacuum contactors utilize vacuum bottle encapsulated contacts to suppress the arc.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] This arc suppression allows the contacts to be much smaller and use less space than air break contacts at higher currents.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] As the contacts are encapsulated, vacuum contactors are used fairly extensively in dirty applications, such as mining.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Vacuum contactors are also widely used at medium voltages from 1000 to 5000 volts, effectively displacing oil-filled circuit breakers in many applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Vacuum contactors are only applicable for use in AC systems.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The AC arc generated upon opening of the contacts will self-extinguish at the zero-crossing of the current waveform, with the vacuum preventing a re-strike of the arc across the open contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Vacuum contactors are therefore very efficient at disrupting the energy of an electric arc and are used when relatively fast switching is required, as the maximum break time is determined by the periodicity of the AC waveform.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] In the case of 60 Hz power (North American standard), the power will discontinue within 1/120 of a second (8.3 ms).
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A mercury relay, sometimes called a mercury displacement relay, or, mercury contactor, is a relay that uses the liquid-metal mercury in an insulated sealed container as the switching element.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] A mercury-wetted relay is a form of relay, usually a reed relay, in which the contacts are wetted with mercury.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] These are not considered contactors because they are not intended for currents above 15 amps.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] To support charging at both 400 V and 800 V DC the Tesla Cybertruck uses a Double-Pole Double-Throw (DPDT) contactor.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] When charging the battery pack of two 400 V modules are connected in either parallel or series by the contactor depending on whether the available voltage is 400 V or 800 V.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] At 800 V the contactor can handle 350 kW.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] When a series of contactors is to be operated in sequence, this may be done by a camshaft instead of by individual electromagnets.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] The camshaft may be driven by an electric motor or a pneumatic cylinder.
[src:solenoids-relays/contactor] Before the advent of solid-state electronics, the camshaft system was commonly used for speed control in electric locomotives.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] An **electromagnet** is a type of magnet in which the magnetic field is produced by an electric current.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Electromagnets usually consist of copper wire wound into a coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A current through the wire creates a magnetic field which is concentrated along the center of the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The magnetic field disappears when the current is turned off.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The wire turns are often wound around a magnetic core made from a ferromagnetic or ferrimagnetic material such as iron; the magnetic core concentrates the magnetic flux and makes a more powerful magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The main advantage of an electromagnet over a permanent magnet is that the magnetic field can be quickly changed by controlling the amount of electric current in the winding.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, unlike a permanent magnet, which needs no power, an electromagnet requires a continuous supply of current to maintain the magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Electromagnets are widely used as components of other electrical devices, such as motors, generators, electromechanical solenoids, relays, loudspeakers, hard disks, MRI machines, scientific instruments, and magnetic separation equipment.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Electromagnets are also employed in industry for picking up and moving heavy iron objects such as scrap iron and steel.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Danish scientist Hans Christian Ørsted discovered in 1820 that electric currents create magnetic fields.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In the same year, the French scientist André-Marie Ampère showed that iron can be magnetized by inserting it into an electrically fed solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] British scientist William Sturgeon invented the electromagnet in 1824.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] His first electromagnet was a horseshoe-shaped piece of iron that was wrapped with about 18 turns of bare copper wire.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] (Insulated wire did not then exist.) The iron was varnished to insulate it from the windings.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] When a current was passed through the coil, the iron became magnetized and attracted other pieces of iron; when the current was stopped, it lost magnetization.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Sturgeon displayed its power by showing that although it only weighed seven ounces (roughly 200 grams), it could lift nine pounds (roughly 4 kilos) when the current of a single-cell power supply was applied.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, Sturgeon's magnets were weak because the uninsulated wire he used could only be wrapped in a single spaced-out layer around the core, limiting the number of turns.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Beginning in 1830, US scientist Joseph Henry systematically improved and popularised the electromagnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] By using wire insulated by silk thread and inspired by Schweigger's use of multiple turns of wire to make a galvanometer, he was able to wind multiple layers of wire onto cores, creating powerful magnets with thousands of turns of wire, including one that could support 2,063 lb (936 kg).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The first major use for electromagnets was in telegraph sounders.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The magnetic domain theory of how ferromagnetic cores work was first proposed in 1906 by French physicist Pierre-Ernest Weiss, and the detailed modern quantum mechanical theory of ferromagnetism was worked out in the 1920s by Werner Heisenberg, Lev Landau, Felix Bloch, and others.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A *portative electromagnet* is one designed to just hold material in place; an example is a lifting magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A *tractive electromagnet* applies a force and moves something.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A common tractive electromagnet is a uniformly wound solenoid and plunger.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The solenoid is a coil of wire, and the plunger is made of a material such as soft iron.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Applying a current to the solenoid applies a force to the plunger and may make it move.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The plunger stops moving when the forces upon it are balanced.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For example, the forces are balanced when the plunger is centered in the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The maximum uniform pull happens when one end of the plunger is at the middle of the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] where C is a proportionality constant, A is the cross-sectional area of the plunger, N is the number of turns in the solenoid, I is the current through the solenoid wire, and ℓ is the length of the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For long, slender, solenoids (in units using inches, pounds force, and amperes), the value of C is around 0.009 to 0.010 psi (maximum pull pounds per square inch of plunger cross-sectional area).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For example, a 12-inch-long coil (*ℓ* = 12 in) with a long plunger with a cross section of one inch square (*A* = 1 in2) and 11,200 ampere-turns (*N I* = 11,200 Aturn) had a maximum pull of 8.75 pounds (corresponding to *C* = 0.0094 psi).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The maximum pull is increased when a magnetic stop is inserted into the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The stop becomes a magnet that will attract the plunger; it adds little to the solenoid pull when the plunger is far away but dramatically increases the pull when the plunger is close.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Here *ℓ*a is the distance between the end of the stop and the end of the plunger.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The additional constant *C*1 for units of inches, pounds, and amperes with slender solenoids is about 2660.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The first term inside the bracket represents the attraction between the stop and the plunger; the second term represents the same force as the solenoid without a stop (**Eq.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Some improvements can be made on this basic design.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The ends of the stop and plunger are often conical.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For example, the plunger may have a pointed end that fits into a matching recess in the stop.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The shape makes the solenoid's pull more uniform as a function of separation.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Another improvement is to add a magnetic return path around the outside of the solenoid (an "iron-clad solenoid").
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The magnetic return path, just as the stop, has little impact until the air gap is small.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] An electric current flowing in a wire creates a magnetic field around the wire, due to Ampere's law *(see drawing of wire with magnetic field)*.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] To concentrate the magnetic field in an electromagnet, the wire is wound into a coil with many turns of wire lying side-by-side.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The magnetic field of all the turns of wire passes through the center of the coil, creating a strong magnetic field there.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A coil forming the shape of a straight tube (a helix) is called a solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The direction of the magnetic field through a coil of wire can be determined by the right-hand rule.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] If the fingers of the right hand are curled around the coil in the direction of current flow (conventional current, flow of positive charge) through the windings, the thumb points in the direction of the field inside the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The side of the magnet that the field lines emerge from is defined to be the *north pole*.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Much stronger magnetic fields can be produced if a magnetic core, made of a soft ferromagnetic (or ferrimagnetic) material such as iron, is placed inside the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A core can increase the magnetic field to thousands of times the strength of the field of the coil alone, due to the high magnetic permeability $\mu$ of the material.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Not all electromagnets use cores, so this is called a *ferromagnetic-core* or *iron-core* electromagnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This phenomenon occurs because the magnetic core's material (often iron or steel) is composed of small regions called magnetic domains that act like tiny magnets (see ferromagnetism).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Before the current in the electromagnet is turned on, these domains point in random directions, so their tiny magnetic fields cancel each other out, and the core has no large-scale magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] When a current passes through the wire wrapped around the core, its magnetic field penetrates the core and turns the domains to align in parallel with the field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] As they align, all their tiny magnetic fields add to the wire's field, which creates a large magnetic field that extends into the space around the magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The core concentrates the field, and the magnetic field passes through the core in lower reluctance than it would when passing through air.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The larger the current passed through the wire coil, the more the domains align, and the stronger the magnetic field is.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Once all the domains are aligned, any additional current only causes a slight increase in the strength of the magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Eventually, the field strength levels off and becomes nearly constant, regardless of how much current is sent through the windings.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This phenomenon is called saturation, and is the main nonlinear feature of ferromagnetic materials.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For most high-permeability core steels, the maximum possible strength of the magnetic field is around 1.6 to 2 teslas (T).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This is why the very strongest electromagnets, such as superconducting and very high current electromagnets, cannot use cores.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] When the current in the coil is turned off, most of the domains in the core material lose alignment and return to a random state, and the electromagnetic field disappears.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, some of the alignment persists because the domains resist turning their direction of magnetization, which leaves the core magnetized as a weak permanent magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This phenomenon is called hysteresis and the remaining magnetic field is called remanent magnetism.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The residual magnetization of the core can be removed by degaussing.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In alternating current electromagnets, such as those used in motors, the core's magnetization is constantly reversed, and the remanence contributes to the motor's losses.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] which says that the integral of the magnetizing field $\mathbf {H}$ around any closed loop is equal to the sum of the current flowing through the loop.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A related equation is the Biot–Savart law, which gives the magnetic field due to each small segment of current.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This equation can be derived from the energy stored in a magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Rearranging terms yields the equation above.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] for the core's saturation limit, $B_{sat}$ .
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In more intuitive units, it is useful to remember that at 1 T the magnetic pressure is approximately 4 standard atmospheres (4.1 kg/cm2).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Given a core geometry, the magnetic field needed for a given force can be calculated from (**Eq.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] 2**); if the result is much more than 1.6 T, a larger core must be used.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, computing the magnetic field and force exerted by ferromagnetic materials in general is difficult for two reasons.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] First, the strength of the field varies from point to point in a complicated way, particularly outside the core and in air gaps, where *fringing fields* and *leakage flux* must be considered.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Second, the magnetic field and force are nonlinear functions of the current, depending on the nonlinear relation between B and $\mathbf {H}$ for the particular core material used.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For precise calculations, computer programs that can produce a model of the magnetic field using the finite element method are employed.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In many practical applications of electromagnets, such as motors, generators, transformers, lifting magnets, and loudspeakers, the iron core is in the form of a loop or magnetic circuit, possibly broken by a few narrow air gaps.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Iron presents much less "resistance" (reluctance) to the magnetic field than air, so a stronger field can be obtained if most of the magnetic field's path is within the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Since the magnetic field lines are closed loops, the core is usually made in the form of a loop.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Since most of the magnetic field is confined within the outlines of the core loop, this allows a simplification of the mathematical analysis.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A common simplifying assumption satisfied by many electromagnets, which will be used in this section, is that the magnetic field strength *B* is constant around the magnetic circuit (within the core and air gaps) and zero outside it.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Most of the magnetic field will be concentrated in the core material (*C*) (see Fig.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Within the core, the magnetic field (*B*) will be approximately uniform across any cross-section; if the core also has roughly constant area throughout its length, the field in the core will be constant.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] At any air gaps (*G*) between core sections, the magnetic field lines are no longer confined by the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Here, they bulge out beyond the core geometry over the length of the gap, reducing the field strength in the gap.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The "bulges" (*BF*) are called fringing fields.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, as long as the length of the gap is smaller than the cross-section dimensions of the core, the field in the gap will be approximately the same as in the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In addition, some of the magnetic field lines (*BL*) will take "short cuts" and not pass through the entire core circuit, and thus will not contribute to the force exerted by the magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This also includes field lines that encircle the wire windings but do not enter the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The magnetic field created by an electromagnet is proportional to both the number of turns of wire N and the current I ; their product, $NI$ , is called magnetomotive force.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This is a nonlinear equation, because the permeability of the core $\mu$ varies with B .
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For an exact solution, $\mu (B)$ must be obtained from the core material hysteresis curve.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] If B is unknown, the equation must be solved by numerical methods.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, if the magnetomotive force is well above saturation (so the core material is in saturation), the magnetic field will be approximately the material's saturation value $B_{sat}$ , and will not vary much with changes in $NI$ .
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For a closed magnetic circuit (no air gap), most core materials saturate at a magnetomotive force of roughly 800 ampere-turns per meter of flux path.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For most core materials, the relative permeability $\mu _{r}\approx 2000{\text{–}}6000\,$ .
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Therefore, in magnetic circuits with an air gap, B depends strongly on the length of the air gap, and the length of the flux path in the core does not matter much.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Given an air gap of 1mm, a magnetomotive force of about 796 ampere-turns is required to produce a magnetic field of 1 T.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For a closed magnetic circuit (no air gap), such as would be found in an electromagnet lifting a piece of iron bridged across its poles, equation (**Eq.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] To maximize the force, a core with a short flux path *L* and a wide cross-sectional area *A* is preferred (this also applies to magnets with an air gap).
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] To achieve this, in applications like lifting magnets and loudspeakers, a flat cylindrical design is often used.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The winding is wrapped around a short wide cylindrical core that forms one pole, and a thick metal housing that wraps around the outside of the windings forms the other part of the magnetic circuit, bringing the magnetic field to the front to form the other pole.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The previous methods are applicable to electromagnets with a magnetic circuit; however, they do not apply when a large part of the magnetic field path is outside the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] (A non-circuit example would be a magnet with a straight cylindrical core.) To determine the force between two electromagnets (or permanent magnets) in these cases, a special analogy called a *magnetic-charge model* can be used.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In this model, it is assumed that the magnets have well-defined "poles" where the field lines emerge from the core, and that the magnetic field is produced by fictitious "magnetic charges" on the surface of the poles.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This model assumes point-like poles (instead of surfaces), and thus it only yields a good approximation when the distance between the magnets is much larger than their diameter; thus, it is useful just for determining a force between them.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] There are several side effects which occur in electromagnets, which must be considered in their design.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] These effects generally become more significant in larger electromagnets.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The only power consumed in a direct current (DC) electromagnet under steady-state conditions is due to the resistance of the windings, and is dissipated as heat.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Some large electromagnets require water cooling systems in the windings to carry off the waste heat.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Since the magnetic field is proportional to the product $NI$ , the number of turns in the windings N and the current I can be chosen to minimize heat losses, as long as their product is constant.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For example, halving I and doubling N halves the power loss, as does doubling the area of the wire.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In either case, increasing the amount of wire reduces the ohmic losses.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] For this reason, electromagnet windings often have a significant thickness.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, the limit to increasing N or lowering the resistance is that the windings take up more space between the magnet's core pieces.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] If the area available for windings is filled up, adding more turns requires a smaller diameter of wire, which has higher resistance, and thus cancels the advantage of using more turns.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] So, in large magnets there is a minimum amount of heat loss that cannot be reduced.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This increases with the square of the magnetic flux, $B^{2}$ .
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] An electromagnet has significant inductance, and resists changes in the current through its windings.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Any sudden changes in the winding current cause large voltage spikes across the windings.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This is because when the current through the magnet is increased, such as when it is turned on, energy from the circuit must be stored in the magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] When it is turned off, the energy in the field is returned to the circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] If an ordinary switch is used to control the winding current, this can cause sparks at the terminals of the switch.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This does not occur when the magnet is switched on, because the limited supply voltage causes the current through the magnet and the field energy to increase slowly.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] But when it is switched off, the energy in the magnetic field is suddenly returned to the circuit, causing a large voltage spike and an arc across the switch contacts, which can damage them.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] With small electromagnets, a capacitor is sometimes used across the contacts, which reduces arcing by temporarily storing the current.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] More often, a diode is used to prevent voltage spikes by providing a path for the current to recirculate through the winding until the energy is dissipated as heat.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The diode is connected across the winding, oriented so it is reverse-biased during steady state operation and does not conduct.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] When the supply voltage is removed, the voltage spike forward-biases the diode and the reactive current continues to flow through the winding, through the diode, and back into the winding.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] A diode used in this way is called a freewheeling diode or flyback diode.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Large electromagnets are usually powered by variable current electronic power supplies, controlled by a microprocessor, which prevent voltage spikes by accomplishing current changes slowly, in gentle ramps.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] It may take several minutes to energize or deenergize a large magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In powerful electromagnets, the magnetic field exerts a force on each turn of the windings, due to the Lorentz force $q\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {B}$ acting on the moving charges within the wire.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The Lorentz force is perpendicular to both the axis of the wire and the magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] It can be visualized as a pressure between the magnetic field lines, pushing them apart.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The Lorentz forces increase with *$B^{2}$*.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In large electromagnets the windings must be firmly clamped in place, to prevent motion on power-up and power-down from causing metal fatigue in the windings.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In the Bitter electromagnet design (Fig.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] 2), used in very high-field research magnets, the windings are constructed as flat disks to resist the radial forces, and clamped in an axial direction to resist the axial ones.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] In alternating current (AC) electromagnets, used in transformers, inductors, and AC motors and generators, the magnetic field is constantly changing.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This causes energy losses in their magnetic cores, which is dissipated as heat in the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The losses stem from two processes: eddy currents and hysteresis losses.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] When a magnetic field higher than the ferromagnetic limit of 1.6 T is needed, superconducting electromagnets can be used.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Instead of using ferromagnetic materials, these use superconducting windings cooled with liquid helium, which conduct current without electrical resistance.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] These allow enormous currents to flow, which generate intense magnetic fields.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Superconducting magnets are limited by the field strength at which the winding material ceases to be superconducting.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Current designs are limited to 10–20 T, with the current (2017) record of 32 T.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The necessary refrigeration equipment and cryostat make them much more expensive than ordinary electromagnets.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] However, in high-power applications this can be offset by lower operating costs, since after startup no power is required for the windings, since no energy is lost to ohmic heating.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] They are used in particle accelerators and MRI machines.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Both iron-core and superconducting electromagnets have limits to the field they can produce.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Therefore, the most powerful man-made magnetic fields have been generated by *air-core* non-superconducting electromagnets of a design invented by Francis Bitter in 1933, called Bitter electromagnets.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] Instead of wire windings, a Bitter magnet consists of a solenoid made of a stack of conducting disks, arranged so that the current moves in a helical path through them, with a hole through the center where the maximum field is created.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] This design has the mechanical strength to withstand the extreme Lorentz forces of the field, which increase with *$B^{2}$*.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The disks are pierced with holes through which cooling water passes to carry away the heat caused by the high current.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The strongest continuous field achieved solely with a resistive magnet is 41.5 T as of 22 August 2017, produced by a Bitter electromagnet at the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory in Tallahassee, Florida.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The strongest continuous magnetic field overall, 45 T, was achieved in June 2000 with a hybrid device consisting of a Bitter magnet inside a superconducting magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The most powerful man-made magnetic fields have been created by using explosives to compress the magnetic field inside an electromagnet as it is pulsed; these are called explosively pumped flux compression generators.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] The implosion compresses the magnetic field to values of around 1,000 T for a few microseconds.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] While this method may seem very destructive, shaped charges redirect the blast outward to minimize harm to the experiment.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] These devices are known as *destructive pulsed electromagnets*.
[src:solenoids-relays/electromagnet] They are used in physics and materials science research to study the properties of materials at high magnetic fields.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A **relay** is an electrically operated switch.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] It has a set of input terminals for one or more control signals, and a set of operating contact terminals.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The switch may have any number of contacts in multiple contact forms, such as make contacts, break contacts, or combinations thereof.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays are used to control a circuit by an independent low-power signal and to control several circuits by one signal.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] They were first used in long-distance telegraph circuits as signal repeaters that transmit a refreshed copy of the incoming signal onto another circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays were used extensively in telephone exchanges and early computers to perform logical operations.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The traditional electromechanical relay uses an electromagnet to close or open the contacts, but relays using other operating principles have also been invented, such as in solid-state relays which use semiconductor properties for control without relying on moving parts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays with calibrated operating characteristics and sometimes multiple operating coils are used to protect electrical circuits from overload or faults; in modern electric power systems these functions are performed by digital instruments still called *protective relays* or *safety relays*.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Latching relays require only a single pulse of control power to operate the switch persistently.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Another pulse applied to a second set of control terminals, or a pulse with opposite polarity, resets the switch, while repeated pulses of the same kind have no effects.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Magnetic latching relays are useful in applications when interrupted power should not affect the circuits that the relay is controlling.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In 1809 an electrolytic relay was designed as an alarm for an electrochemical telegraph by Samuel Thomas von Sömmerring.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Electrical relays got their start mainly in application to telegraphs.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] American scientist Joseph Henry is often cited to have invented a relay in 1835 in order to improve his version of the electrical telegraph, developed earlier in 1831.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] However, Henry never published any of these experiments and dating for his relay experiments is based solely on the words of Henry himself and his students, often decades later.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] He did this two months before Charles Wheatstone and William Cooke filed their first patent for their telegraph system and would file a patent for the same idea a year later.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] However, an official patent was not issued until 1840 to Samuel Morse for his telegraph, which is now called a relay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The mechanism described acted as a digital amplifier, repeating the telegraph signal, and thus allowing signals to be propagated as far as desired.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The word *relay* appears in the context of electromagnetic operations from 1860 onwards.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A simple electromagnetic relay consists of a coil of wire wrapped around a soft iron core (a solenoid), an iron yoke which provides a low reluctance path for magnetic flux, a movable iron armature, and one or more sets of contacts (there are two contacts in the relay pictured).
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The armature is hinged to the yoke and mechanically linked to one or more sets of moving contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The armature is held in place by a spring so that when the relay is de-energized there is an air gap in the magnetic circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In this condition, one of the two sets of contacts in the relay pictured is closed, and the other set is open.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Other relays may have more or fewer sets of contacts depending on their function.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The relay in the picture also has a wire connecting the armature to the yoke.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This ensures continuity of the circuit between the moving contacts on the armature, and the circuit track on the printed circuit board (PCB) via the yoke, which is soldered to the PCB.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] When an electric current is passed through the coil it generates a magnetic field that activates the armature, and the consequent movement of the movable contact(s) either makes or breaks (depending upon construction) a connection with a fixed contact.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] If the set of contacts was closed when the relay was de-energized, then the movement opens the contacts and breaks the connection, and vice versa if the contacts were open.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] When the current to the coil is switched off, the armature is returned by a force, approximately half as strong as the magnetic force, to its relaxed position.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Usually this force is provided by a spring, but gravity is also used commonly in industrial motor starters.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Most relays are manufactured to operate quickly.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In a low-voltage application this reduces noise; in a high voltage or current application it reduces arcing.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] When the coil is energized with direct current, a flyback diode or snubber resistor is often placed across the coil to dissipate the energy from the collapsing magnetic field (back EMF) at deactivation, which would otherwise generate a voltage spike dangerous to semiconductor circuit components.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Such diodes were not widely used before the application of transistors as relay drivers, but soon became ubiquitous as early germanium transistors were easily destroyed by this surge.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Some automotive relays include a diode inside the relay case.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Resistors, while more durable than diodes, are less efficient at eliminating voltage spikes generated by relays and therefore not as commonly used.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] If the relay is driving a large, or especially a reactive load, there may be a similar problem of surge currents around the relay output contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In this case a snubber circuit (a capacitor and resistor in series) across the contacts may absorb the surge.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Suitably rated capacitors and the associated resistor are sold as a single packaged component for this commonplace use.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] If the coil is designed to be energized with alternating current (AC), some method is used to split the flux into two out-of-phase components which add together, increasing the minimum pull on the armature during the AC cycle.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Typically this is done with a small copper "shading ring" crimped around a portion of the core that creates the delayed, out-of-phase component, which holds the contacts during the zero crossings of the control voltage.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Contact materials for relays vary by application.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Materials with low contact resistance may be oxidized by the air, or may tend to "stick" instead of cleanly parting when opening.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Contact material may be optimized for low electrical resistance, high strength to withstand repeated operations, or high capacity to withstand the heat of an arc.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Where very low resistance is required, or low thermally-induced voltages are desired, gold-plated contacts may be used, along with palladium and other non-oxidizing, semi-precious metals.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Silver or silver-plated contacts are used for signal switching.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Mercury-wetted relays make and break circuits using a thin, self-renewing film of liquid mercury.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For higher-power relays switching many amperes, such as motor circuit contactors, contacts are made with a mixtures of silver and cadmium oxide, providing low contact resistance and high resistance to the heat of arcing.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Contacts used in circuits carrying scores or hundreds of amperes may include additional structures for heat dissipation and management of the arc produced when interrupting the circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Some relays have field-replaceable contacts, such as certain machine tool relays; these may be replaced when worn out, or changed between normally open and normally closed state, to allow for changes in the controlled circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Since relays are switches, the terminology applied to switches is also applied to relays; a relay switches one or more *poles*, each of whose contacts can be *thrown* by energizing the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Normally open (NO) contacts connect the circuit when the relay is activated; the circuit is disconnected when the relay is inactive.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Normally closed (NC) contacts disconnect the circuit when the relay is activated; the circuit is connected when the relay is inactive.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] All of the contact forms involve combinations of NO and NC connections.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In the US, the National Association of Relay Manufacturers and its successor, the Relay and Switch Industry Association define 23 distinct electrical contact forms found in relays and switches.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The *S* (*single*) or *D* (*double*) designator for the pole count may be replaced with a number, indicating multiple contacts connected to a single actuator.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For example, 4PDT indicates a four-pole double-throw relay that has 12 switching terminals.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Where radio transmitters and receivers share one antenna, often a coaxial relay is used as a TR (transmit-receive) relay, which switches the antenna from the receiver to the transmitter.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This protects the receiver from the high power of the transmitter.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Such relays are often used in transceivers which combine transmitter and receiver in one unit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The relay contacts are designed not to reflect any radio frequency power back toward the source, and to provide very high isolation between receiver and transmitter terminals.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The characteristic impedance of the relay is matched to the transmission line impedance of the system, for example, 50 ohms.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A contactor is a heavy-duty relay with higher current ratings, used for switching electric motors and lighting loads.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Continuous current ratings for common contactors range from 10 amps to several hundred amps.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] High-current contacts are made with alloys containing silver.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The unavoidable arcing causes the contacts to oxidize; however, silver oxide is still a good conductor.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Contactors with overload protection devices are often used to start motors.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A force-guided contacts relay has relay contacts that are mechanically linked together, so that when the relay coil is energized or de-energized, all of the linked contacts move together.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] If one set of contacts in the relay becomes immobilized, no other contact of the same relay will be able to move.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The function of force-guided contacts is to enable the safety circuit to check the status of the relay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Force-guided contacts are also known as "positive-guided contacts", "captive contacts", "locked contacts", "mechanically linked contacts", or "safety relays".
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] These safety relays have to follow design rules and manufacturing rules that are defined in one main machinery standard EN 50205 : Relays with forcibly guided (mechanically linked) contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] These rules for the safety design are the one defined in type B standards such as EN 13849-2 as Basic safety principles and Well-tried safety principles for machinery that applies to all machines.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Force-guided contacts by themselves can not guarantee that all contacts are in the same state, however, they do guarantee, subject to no gross mechanical fault, that no contacts are in opposite states.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Otherwise, a relay with several normally open (NO) contacts may stick when energized, with some contacts closed and others still slightly open, due to mechanical tolerances.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Similarly, a relay with several normally closed (NC) contacts may stick to the unenergized position, so that when energized, the circuit through one set of contacts is broken, with a marginal gap, while the other remains closed.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] By introducing both NO and NC contacts, or more commonly, changeover contacts, on the same relay, it then becomes possible to guarantee that if any NC contact is closed, all NO contacts are open, and conversely, if any NO contact is closed, all NC contacts are open.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Force-guided contact relays are made with different main contact sets, either NO, NC or changeover, and one or more auxiliary contact sets, often of reduced current or voltage rating, used for the monitoring system.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Contacts may be all NO, all NC, changeover, or a mixture of these, for the monitoring contacts, so that the safety system designer can select the correct configuration for the particular application.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Safety relays are used as part of an engineered safety system.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A latching relay, also called *impulse*, *bistable*, *keep*, or *stay* relay, or simply *latch*, maintains either contact position indefinitely without power applied to the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The advantage is that one coil consumes power only for an instant while the relay is being switched, and the relay contacts retain this setting across a power outage.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A latching relay allows remote control of building lighting without the hum that may be produced from a continuously (AC) energized coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In one mechanism, two opposing coils with an over-center spring or permanent magnet hold the contacts in position after the coil is de-energized.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A pulse to one coil turns the relay on, and a pulse to the opposite coil turns the relay off.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This type is widely used where control is from simple switches or single-ended outputs of a control system, and such relays are found in avionics and numerous industrial applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Another latching type has a remanent core that retains the contacts in the operated position by the remanent magnetism in the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This type requires a current pulse of opposite polarity to release the contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A variation uses a permanent magnet that produces part of the force required to close the contact; the coil supplies sufficient force to move the contact open or closed by aiding or opposing the field of the permanent magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A polarity controlled relay needs changeover switches or an H-bridge drive circuit to control it.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The relay may be less expensive than other types, but this is partly offset by the increased costs in the external circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In another type, a *ratchet relay* has a ratchet mechanism that holds the contacts closed after the coil is momentarily energized.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A second impulse, in the same or a separate coil, releases the contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This type may be found in certain cars, for headlamp dipping and other functions where alternating operation on each switch actuation is needed.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A stepping relay is a specialized kind of multi-way latching relay designed for early automatic telephone exchanges.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] An earth-leakage circuit breaker includes a specialized latching relay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Very early computers often stored bits in a magnetically latching relay, such as ferreed or the later remreed in the 1ESS switch.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Some early computers used ordinary relays as a kind of latch—they store bits in ordinary wire-spring relays or reed relays by feeding an output wire back as an input, resulting in a feedback loop or sequential circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Such an electrically latching relay requires continuous power to maintain state, unlike magnetically latching relays or mechanically ratcheting relays.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] While '(self-)holding circuits' are often realized with relays they can also be implemented by other means.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In computer memories, latching relays and other relays were replaced by delay-line memory, which in turn was replaced by a series of ever faster and ever smaller memory technologies.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A machine tool relay is a type standardized for industrial control of machine tools, transfer machines, and other sequential control.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] They are characterized by a large number of contacts (sometimes extendable in the field) which are easily converted from normally open to normally closed status, easily replaceable coils, and a form factor that allows compactly installing many relays in a control panel.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Although such relays once were the backbone of automation in such industries as automobile assembly, the programmable logic controller (PLC) mostly displaced the machine tool relay from sequential control applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A relay allows circuits to be switched by electrical equipment: for example, a timer circuit with a relay could switch power at a preset time.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For many years relays were the standard method of controlling industrial electronic systems.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A number of relays could be used together to carry out complex functions (relay logic).
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The principle of relay logic is based on relays which energize and de-energize associated contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relay logic is the predecessor of ladder logic, which is commonly used in programmable logic controllers.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A mercury relay is a relay that uses mercury as the switching element.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] They are used where contact erosion would be a problem for conventional relay contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Owing to environmental considerations about significant amount of mercury used and modern alternatives, they are now comparatively uncommon.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A mercury-wetted reed relay is a form of reed relay that employs a mercury switch, in which the contacts are wetted with mercury.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Mercury reduces the contact resistance and mitigates the associated voltage drop.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Surface contamination may result in poor conductivity for low-current signals.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For high-speed applications, the mercury eliminates contact bounce, and provides virtually instantaneous circuit closure.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Mercury wetted relays are position-sensitive and must be mounted according to the manufacturer's specifications.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Because of the toxicity and expense of liquid mercury, these relays have increasingly fallen into disuse.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The high speed of switching action of the mercury-wetted relay is a notable advantage.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The mercury globules on each contact coalesce, and the current rise time through the contacts is generally considered to be a few picoseconds.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] However, in a practical circuit it may be limited by the inductance of the contacts and wiring.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The same coalescence process causes another effect, which is a nuisance in some applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The contact resistance is not stable immediately after contact closure, and drifts, mostly downwards, for several seconds after closure, the change perhaps being 0.5 ohm.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Multi-voltage relays are devices designed to work for wide voltage ranges such as 24 to 240 VAC and VDC and wide frequency ranges such as 0 to 300 Hz.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] They are indicated for use in installations that do not have stable supply voltages.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Electric motors need overcurrent protection to prevent damage from over-loading the motor, or to protect against short circuits in connecting cables or internal faults in the motor windings.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The overload sensing devices are a form of heat operated relay where a coil heats a bimetallic strip, or where a solder pot melts, to operate auxiliary contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] These auxiliary contacts are in series with the motor's contactor coil, so they turn off the motor when it overheats.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This thermal protection operates relatively slowly allowing the motor to draw higher starting currents before the protection relay will trip.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Where the overload relay is exposed to the same ambient temperature as the motor, a useful though crude compensation for motor ambient temperature is provided.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The other common overload protection system uses an electromagnet coil in series with the motor circuit that directly operates contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This is similar to a control relay but requires a rather high fault current to operate the contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] To prevent short over current spikes from causing nuisance triggering the armature movement is damped with a dashpot.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The thermal and magnetic overload detections are typically used together in a motor protection relay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Electronic overload protection relays measure motor current and can estimate motor winding temperature using a "thermal model" of the motor armature system that can be set to provide more accurate motor protection.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Some motor protection relays include temperature detector inputs for direct measurement from a thermocouple or resistance thermometer sensor embedded in the winding.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A polarized relay places the armature between the poles of a permanent magnet to increase sensitivity.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Polarized relays were used in middle 20th Century telephone exchanges to detect faint pulses and correct telegraphic distortion.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A reed relay is a reed switch enclosed in a solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The switch has a set of contacts inside an evacuated or inert gas-filled glass tube that protects the contacts against atmospheric corrosion; the contacts are made of magnetic material that makes them move under the influence of the field of the enclosing solenoid or an external magnet.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Reed relays can switch faster than larger relays and require very little power from the control circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] However, they have relatively low switching current and voltage ratings.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Though rare, the reeds can become magnetized over time, which makes them stick "on", even when no current is present; changing the orientation of the reeds or degaussing the switch with respect to the solenoid's magnetic field can resolve this problem.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Sealed contacts with mercury-wetted contacts have longer operating lives and less contact chatter than any other kind of relay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Safety relays are devices which generally implement protection functions.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In the event of a hazard, the task of such a safety function is to use appropriate measures to reduce the existing risk to an acceptable level.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A solid-state contactor is a heavy-duty solid state relay, including the necessary heat sink, used where frequent on-off cycles are required, such as with electric heaters, small electric motors, and lighting loads.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] There are no moving parts to wear out and there is no contact bounce due to vibration.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] They are activated by AC control signals or DC control signals from programmable logic controllers (PLCs), PCs, transistor-transistor logic (TTL) sources, or other microprocessor and microcontroller controls.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A solid-state relay (SSR) is a solid state electronic component that provides a function similar to an electromechanical relay but does not have any moving components, increasing long-term reliability.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A solid-state relay uses a thyristor, TRIAC or other solid-state switching device, activated by the control signal, to switch the controlled load, instead of a solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] An optocoupler (a light-emitting diode (LED) coupled with a photo transistor) can be used to isolate control and controlled circuits.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A static relay consists of electronic circuitry to emulate all those characteristics which are achieved by moving parts in an electro-magnetic relay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Timing relays are arranged for an intentional delay in operating their contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A very short (a fraction of a second) delay would use a copper disk between the armature and moving blade assembly.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Current flowing in the disk maintains a magnetic field for a short time, lengthening release time.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For a slightly longer (up to a minute) delay, a dashpot is used.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A dashpot is a piston filled with fluid that is allowed to escape slowly; both air-filled and oil-filled dashpots are used.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The time period can be varied by increasing or decreasing the flow rate.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For longer time periods, a mechanical clockwork timer is installed.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays may be arranged for a fixed timing period, or may be field-adjustable, or remotely set from a control panel.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Modern microprocessor-based timing relays provide precision timing over a great range.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Some relays are constructed with a kind of "shock absorber" mechanism attached to the armature, which prevents immediate, full motion when the coil is either energized or de-energized.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This addition gives the relay the property of time-delay actuation.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Time-delay relays can be constructed to delay armature motion on coil energization, de-energization, or both.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Time-delay relay contacts must be specified not only as either normally open or normally closed, but whether the delay operates in the direction of closing, opening, or both.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The following is a description of the four basic types of time-delay relay contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] First, we have the normally open, timed-closed (NOTC) contact.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This type of contact is normally open when the coil is unpowered (de-energized).
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The contact is closed by the application of power to the relay coil, but only after the coil has been continuously powered for the specified amount of time.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In other words, the direction of the contact's motion (either to close or to open) is identical to a regular NO contact, but there is a delay in closing direction.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Because the delay occurs in the direction of coil energization, this type of contact is alternatively known as a normally open, on-delay.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] A vacuum relay is a sensitive relay having its contacts mounted in an evacuated glass housing, to permit handling radio-frequency voltages as high as 20,000 volts without flashover between contacts even though contact spacing is as low as a few hundredths of an inch when open.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays are used wherever it is necessary to control a high power or high voltage circuit with a low power circuit, especially when galvanic isolation is desirable.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The first application of relays was in long telegraph lines, whereas the weak signal received at an intermediate station could control a contact, regenerating the signal for further transmission.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] High-voltage or high-current devices can be controlled with small, low voltage wiring and pilots switches.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Operators can be isolated from the high voltage circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Low power devices such as microprocessors can drive relays to control electrical loads beyond their direct drive capability.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In an automobile, a starter relay allows the high current of the cranking motor to be controlled with small wiring and contacts in the ignition key.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Electromechanical switching systems including Strowger and crossbar telephone exchanges made extensive use of relays in ancillary control circuits.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The Relay Automatic Telephone Company also manufactured telephone exchanges based solely on relay switching techniques designed by Gotthilf Ansgarius Betulander.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The first public relay based telephone exchange in the UK was installed in Fleetwood on 15 July 1922 and remained in service until 1959.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The use of relays for the logical control of complex switching systems like telephone exchanges was studied by Claude Shannon, who formalized the application of Boolean algebra to relay circuit design in *A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits*.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays can perform the basic operations of Boolean combinatorial logic.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For example, the Boolean AND function is realised by connecting normally open relay contacts in series, the OR function by connecting normally open contacts in parallel.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Inversion of a logical input can be done with a normally closed contact.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays were used for control of automated systems for machine tools and production lines.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The Ladder programming language is often used for designing relay logic networks.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Early electro-mechanical computers such as the ARRA, Harvard Mark II, Zuse Z2, and Zuse Z3 used relays for logic and working registers.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] However, electronic devices proved faster and easier to use.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Relays are much more resistant than semiconductors to nuclear radiation, so they are widely used in safety-critical logic, such as the control panels of radioactive waste-handling machinery.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Electromechanical protective relays are used to detect overload and other faults on electrical lines by opening and closing circuit breakers.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] For protection of electrical apparatus and transmission lines, electromechanical relays with accurate operating characteristics were used to detect overload, short-circuits, and other faults.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] While many such relays remain in use, digital protective relays now provide equivalent and more complex protective functions.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Railway signalling relays are large considering the mostly small voltages (less than 120 V) and currents (perhaps 100 mA) that they switch.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Contacts are widely spaced to prevent flashovers and short circuits over a lifetime that may exceed fifty years.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Since rail signal circuits must be highly reliable, special techniques are used to detect and prevent failures in the relay system.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] To protect against false feeds, double switching relay contacts are often used on both the positive and negative side of a circuit, so that two false feeds are needed to cause a false signal.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Not all relay circuits can be proved so there is reliance on construction features such as carbon to silver contacts to resist lightning induced contact welding and to provide AC immunity.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Opto-isolators are also used in some instances with railway signalling, especially where only a single contact is to be switched.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] There are many considerations involved in the correct selection of a control relay for a particular application, including factors such as speed of operation, sensitivity, and hysteresis.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Although typical control relays operate in the 5 ms to 20 ms range, relays with switching speeds as fast as 100 μs are available.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Reed relays which are actuated by low currents and switch fast are suitable for controlling small currents.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] As with any switch, the contact current (unrelated to the coil current) must not exceed a given value to avoid damage.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In high-inductance circuits such as motors, other issues must be addressed.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] When an inductance is connected to a power source, an input surge current or electromotor starting current larger than the steady-state current exists.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] When the circuit is broken, the current cannot change instantaneously, which creates a potentially damaging arc across the separating contacts.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Consequently, for relays used to control inductive loads, we must specify the maximum current that may flow through the relay contacts when it actuates, the *make rating*; the continuous rating; and the *break rating*.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The make rating may be several times larger than the continuous rating, which is larger than the break rating.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Switching while "wet" (under load) causes undesired arcing between the contacts, eventually leading to contacts that weld shut or contacts that fail due to a buildup of surface damage caused by the destructive arc energy.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Inside the Number One Electronic Switching System (1ESS) crossbar switch and certain other high-reliability designs, the reed switches are always switched "dry" (without load) to avoid that problem, leading to much longer contact life.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Without adequate contact protection, the occurrence of electric current arcing causes significant degradation of the contacts, which suffer significant and visible damage.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Every time the relay contacts open or close under load, an electrical arc can occur between the contacts of the relay, either a *break* arc (when opening), or a *make* / *bounce* arc (when closing).
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] In many situations, the *break* arc is more energetic and thus more destructive, in particular with inductive loads, but this can be mitigated by bridging the contacts with a snubber circuit.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The inrush current of tungsten filament incandescent lamps is typically ten times the normal operating current.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Thus, relays intended for tungsten loads may use special contact composition, or the relay may have lower contact ratings for tungsten loads than for purely resistive loads.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] An electrical arc across relay contacts can be very hot — thousands of degrees Fahrenheit — causing the metal on the contact surfaces to melt, pool, and migrate with the current.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] The extremely high temperature of the arc splits the surrounding gas molecules, creating ozone, carbon monoxide, and other compounds.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] Over time, the arc energy slowly destroys the contact metal, causing some material to escape into the air as fine particulate matter.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This action causes the material in the contacts to degrade and coordination, resulting in device failure.
[src:solenoids-relays/relay] This contact degradation drastically limits the overall life of a relay to a range of about 10,000 to 100,000 operations, a level far below the mechanical life of the device, which can be in excess of 20 million operations.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A **solenoid valve** is an electromechanically operated valve used in heating systems, fuel pipelines, and industrial automation to regulate the flow of liquids or gases.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] It works by passing electric current through a coil of wire, which creates a magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The magnetic field attracts a plunger, which operates the valve mechanism, to open or close fluid passages.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoid valves differ in the characteristics of the specific electric current in which they use, the strength of the electromagnetic field that they generate, the mechanism they use to regulate the fluid, and the type and characteristics of fluid they control.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The mechanism varies from linear action, plunger-type actuators to pivoted-armature actuators and rocker actuators.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The valve can use a two-port design to regulate a flow or use a three or more port design to switch flows between ports.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Multiple solenoid valves can be placed together on a manifold.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The valve mechanism operated by the force of the magnetic plunger may be a spool valve, or a poppet-style valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Simple solenoids may use a spring to return the valve to the idle position; more complex valves may have two or more coils to move a spool valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Proportional valves allow a varying electrical current to adjust the position of a valve over a range, which can be used to control flow and thus speed of fluid power devices.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoid valves are the most frequently used control elements in fluidics.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Their tasks are to shut off, release, dose, distribute or mix fluids.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] They are found in many application areas.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoids offer fast and safe switching, high-reliability, long service life, good medium compatibility of the materials used, low control power and compact design.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Ordinary valves can have many ports and fluid paths.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A 2-way valve, for example, has 2 ports; if the valve is **open**, then the two ports are connected and fluid may flow between the ports; if the valve is **closed**, then ports are isolated.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] If the valve is open when the solenoid is not energized, then the valve is termed **normally open** (N.O.).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Similarly, if the valve is closed when the solenoid is not energized, then the valve is termed **normally closed** (N.C.).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] There are also 3-way and more complicated designs.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A 3-way valve has 3 ports; it connects one port to either of the two other ports (typically a supply port and an exhaust port).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoid valves are also characterized by how they operate.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A small solenoid can generate a limited force.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A typical solenoid force might be 15 N (3.4 lbf).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] An application might be a low pressure (e.g., 10 psi (69 kPa)) gas with a small orifice diameter (e.g., 3⁄8 in (9.5 mm) for an orifice area of 0.11 in2 (71 mm2) and approximate force of 1.1 lbf (4.9 N)).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] If the force required is low enough, the solenoid is able to directly actuate the main valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] These are simply called **Direct-Acting** solenoid valves.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] When electricity is supplied, electrical energy is converted to mechanical energy, physically moving a barrier to either obstruct flow (if it is N.O.) or allow flow (if it is N.C.).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A spring is often used to return the valve to its resting position once power is shut off.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Direct-acting valves are useful for their simplicity, although they do require a large amount of power relative to other types of solenoid valves.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] If fluid pressures are high and orifice diameter is large, a solenoid may not generate enough force on its own to actuate the valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] To solve this, a **Pilot-Operated** solenoid valve design can be used.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Such a design uses the pressurized fluid itself to apply the forces required to actuate the valve, with the solenoid as a "pilot" directing the fluid (see subsection below).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] These valves are used in dishwashers, irrigation systems, and other applications where large pressures and/or volumes are desired.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Pilot-operated solenoids tend to consume less energy than direct-action, although they will not work at all without sufficient fluid pressure and are more susceptible to getting clogged if the fluid has solid impurities.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] A direct-acting solenoid valve typically operates in 5 to 10 milliseconds.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Pilot-operated valves are slightly slower; depending on their size, typical values range from 15 to 150 milliseconds.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Power consumption and supply requirements of the solenoid vary with application, being primarily determined by fluid pressure and orifice diameter.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] For example, a popular 3⁄4-inch 150 psi sprinkler valve, intended for 24 VAC (50–60 Hz) residential systems, has a momentary inrush of 7.2 VA, and a holding power requirement of 4.6 VA.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Comparatively, an industrial 1⁄2-inch 10,000 psi valve, intended for 12, 24, or 120 VAC systems in high-pressure fluid and cryogenic applications, has an inrush of 300 VA and a holding power of 22 VA.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Neither valve lists a minimum pressure required to remain closed in the unpowered state.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] While there are multiple design variants, the following is a detailed breakdown of a typical pilot-operated solenoid valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] They may use metal seals or rubber seals, and may also have electrical interfaces to allow for easy control.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The diagram to the right shows the design of a basic valve, controlling the flow of water in this example.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The top half shows the valve in its closed state.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] An inlet stream of pressurized water enters at **A**.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] **B** is an elastic diaphragm and above it is a spring pushing it down.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The diaphragm has a pinhole through its center which allows a very small amount of water to flow through.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] This water fills cavity **C** so that pressure is roughly equal on both sides of the diaphragm.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] However, the pressurized water in cavity **C** acts across a much greater area of the diaphragm than the water in inlet **A**.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] From the equation $F=P*A$ , the force from cavity **C** pushing downward is greater than the force from inlet **A** pushing upward, and the diaphragm remains closed.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Diaphragm **B** will stay closed as long as small drain passage **D** remains blocked by a pin, which is controlled by solenoid **E**.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] In a normally closed valve, supplying an electric current to the solenoid will raise the pin via magnetic force, and the water in cavity **C** drains out through passage **D** faster than the pinhole can refill it.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Less water in cavity **C** means the pressure on that side of the diaphragm drops, proportionately dropping the force too.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] With the downward force of cavity **C** now less than the upward force of inlet **A**, the diaphragm is pushed upward, thus opening the valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Water now flows freely from **A** to **F**.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] When the solenoid is deactivated and passage **D** is closed, water once again accumulates in cavity **C**, closing the diaphragm once the downward force exerted is great enough.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] This process is the opposite for a normally open pilot-operated valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] In that case, the pin is naturally held open by a spring, passage **D** is open, and cavity **C** is never able to fill up enough, pushing open diaphragm **B** and allowing unobstructed flow.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Supplying an electric current to the solenoid pushes the pin into a closed position, blocking passage **D**, allowing water to accumulate in cavity **C**, and ultimately closing diaphragm **B**.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] In this way, a pilot-operated solenoid valve can be conceptualized as two valves working together: a direct-acting solenoid valve which functions as the "brain" to direct the "muscle" of a much more powerful main valve which gets actuated pneumatically or hydraulically.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] This is why pilot-operated valves will not work without a sufficient pressure differential between input and output, the "muscle" needs to be strong enough to push back against the diaphragm and open it.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Should the pressure at the output rise above that of the input, the valve would open regardless of the state of the solenoid and pilot valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoid valve designs have many variations and challenges.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The core or plunger is the magnetic component that moves when the solenoid is energized.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The core's movement will make or break the seals that control the movement of the fluid.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] When the coil is not energized, springs will hold the core in its normal position.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The core tube contains and guides the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] It also retains the plugnut and may seal the fluid.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] To optimize the movement of the core, the core tube needs to be nonmagnetic.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] If the core tube were magnetic, then it would offer a shunt path for the field lines.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] In some designs, the core tube is an enclosed metal shell produced by deep drawing.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Such a design simplifies the sealing problems because the fluid cannot escape from the enclosure, but the design also increases the magnetic path resistance because the magnetic path must traverse the thickness of the core tube twice: once near the plugnut and once near the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] In some other designs, the core tube is not closed but rather an open tube that slips over one end of the plugnut.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] To retain the plugnut, the tube might be crimped to the plugnut.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] An O-ring seal between the tube and the plugnut will prevent the fluid from escaping.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The solenoid coil consists of many turns of copper wire that surround the core tube and induce the movement of the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The coil is often encapsulated in epoxy.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The coil also has an iron frame that provides a low magnetic path resistance.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The valve body must be compatible with the fluid; common materials are brass, stainless steel, aluminum, and plastic.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The seals must be compatible with the fluid.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] To simplify the sealing issues, the plugnut, core, springs, shading ring, and other components are often exposed to the fluid, so they must be compatible as well.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The requirements present some special problems.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The core tube needs to be non-magnetic to pass the solenoid's field through to the plugnut and the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] The plugnut and core need a material with good magnetic properties such as iron, but iron is prone to corrosion.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Stainless steels can be used because they come in both magnetic and non-magnetic varieties.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] For example, a solenoid valve might use 304 stainless steel for the body, 305 stainless steel for the core tube, 302 stainless steel for the springs, and 430 F stainless steel (a magnetic stainless steel) for the core and plugnut.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoid valves are used in fluid power pneumatic and hydraulic systems, to control cylinders, fluid power motors or larger industrial valves.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Automatic irrigation sprinkler systems also use solenoid valves with an automatic controller.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Domestic washing machines and dishwashers use solenoid valves to control water entry into the machine.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] They are also often used in paintball gun triggers to actuate the CO2 hammer valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] Solenoid valves can be used for a wide array of industrial applications, including general on-off control, calibration and test stands, pilot plant control loops, process control systems, and various original equipment manufacturer applications.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid-valve] In 1910, ASCO Numatics became the first company to develop and manufacture the solenoid valve.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] A **solenoid** (/ˈsoʊlənɔɪd/) is a type of electromagnet formed by a helical coil of wire whose length is substantially greater than its diameter, which generates a controlled magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The coil can produce a uniform magnetic field in a volume of space when an electric current is passed through it.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] André-Marie Ampère coined the term *solenoid* in 1823, having conceived of the device in 1820.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The French term originally created by Ampère is *solénoïde*, which is a French transliteration of the Greek word *σωληνοειδής* which means *tubular*.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The helical coil of a solenoid does not necessarily need to revolve around a straight-line axis; for example, William Sturgeon's electromagnet of 1824 consisted of a solenoid bent into a horseshoe shape (similarly to an arc spring).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Solenoids provide magnetic focusing of electrons in vacuums, notably in television camera tubes such as vidicons and image orthicons.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Electrons take helical paths within the magnetic field.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] These solenoids, focus coils, surround nearly the whole length of the tube.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] An infinite solenoid has infinite length but finite diameter.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] "Continuous" means that the solenoid is not formed by discrete finite-width coils but by many infinitely thin coils with no space between them; in this abstraction, the solenoid is often viewed as a cylindrical sheet of conductive material.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The magnetic field inside an infinitely long solenoid is homogeneous and its strength neither depends on the distance from the axis nor on the solenoid's cross-sectional area.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] This is a derivation of the magnetic flux density around a solenoid that is long enough so that fringe effects can be ignored.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] In Figure 1, we immediately know that the flux density vector points in the positive *z* direction inside the solenoid, and in the negative *z* direction outside the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] We confirm this by applying the right hand grip rule for the field around a wire.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] If we wrap our right hand around a wire with the thumb pointing in the direction of the current, the curl of the fingers shows how the field behaves.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Since we are dealing with a long solenoid, all of the components of the magnetic field not pointing upwards cancel out by symmetry.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Outside, a similar cancellation occurs, and the field is only pointing downwards.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Now consider the imaginary loop *c* that is located inside the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] We have shown above that the field is pointing upwards inside the solenoid, so the horizontal portions of loop *c* do not contribute anything to the integral.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Thus the integral of the up side 1 is equal to the integral of the down side 2.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Since we can arbitrarily change the dimensions of the loop and get the same result, the only physical explanation is that the integrands are actually equal, that is, the magnetic field inside the solenoid is radially uniform.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Note, though, that nothing prohibits it from varying longitudinally, which in fact, it does.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] A similar argument can be applied to the loop *a* to conclude that the field outside the solenoid is radially uniform or constant.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] This last result, which holds strictly true only near the center of the solenoid where the field lines are parallel to its length, is important as it shows that the flux density outside is practically zero since the radii of the field outside the solenoid will tend to infinity.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] An intuitive argument can also be used to show that the flux density outside the solenoid is actually zero.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Magnetic field lines only exist as loops, they cannot diverge from or converge to a point like electric field lines can (see Gauss's law for magnetism).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The magnetic field lines follow the longitudinal path of the solenoid inside, so they must go in the opposite direction outside of the solenoid so that the lines can form loops.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] However, the volume outside the solenoid is much greater than the volume inside, so the density of magnetic field lines outside is greatly reduced.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Now recall that the field outside is constant.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] In order for the total number of field lines to be conserved, the field outside must go to zero as the solenoid gets longer.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Of course, if the solenoid is constructed as a wire spiral (as often done in practice), then it emanates an outside field the same way as a single wire, due to the current flowing overall down the length of the solenoid.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] where B is the magnetic flux density, l is the length of the solenoid, $\mu _{0}$ is the magnetic constant, N the number of turns, and I the current.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] This equation is valid for a solenoid in free space, which means the permeability of the magnetic path is the same as permeability of free space, μ0.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] In most solenoids, the solenoid is not immersed in a higher permeability material, but rather some portion of the space around the solenoid has the higher permeability material and some is just air (which behaves much like free space).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] In that scenario, the full effect of the high permeability material is not seen, but there will be an effective (or apparent) permeability *μ*eff such that 1 ≤ *μ*eff ≤ *μ*r.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The inclusion of a ferromagnetic core, such as iron, increases the magnitude of the magnetic flux density in the solenoid and raises the effective permeability of the magnetic path.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] where *μ*eff is the effective or apparent permeability of the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The effective permeability is a function of the geometric properties of the core and its relative permeability.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The terms relative permeability (a property of just the material) and effective permeability (a property of the whole structure) are often confused; they can differ by many orders of magnitude.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Additionally, ferromagnetic cores are subject to magnetic saturation; once the core material is fully magnetized, increasing the current further will not produce a proportional increase in magnetic flux.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] where *k* is the demagnetization factor of the core.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] A finite solenoid is a solenoid with finite length.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Continuous means that the solenoid is not formed by discrete coils but by a sheet of conductive material.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Here, $K(m)$ , $E(m)$ , and $\Pi (n,m)$ are complete elliptic integrals of the first, second, and third kind.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Within the category of finite solenoids, there are those that are sparsely wound with a single pitch, those that are sparsely wound with varying pitches (varied-pitch solenoid), and those with varying radii for different loops (non-cylindrical solenoids).
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] They have found applications in different areas, such as sparsely wound solenoids for wireless power transfer, varied-pitch solenoids for magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and non-cylindrical solenoids for other medical devices.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The calculation of the intrinsic inductance and capacitance cannot be done using those for the conventional solenoids, i.e. the tightly wound ones.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] New calculation methods were proposed for the calculation of intrinsic inductance(codes available at ) and capacitance.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] where *μ*0 is the magnetic constant, N the number of turns, I the current and l the length of the coil.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] A table of inductance for short solenoids of various diameter to length ratios has been calculated by Dellinger, Whittmore, and Ould.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] This, and the inductance of more complicated shapes, can be derived from Maxwell's equations.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] For rigid air-core coils, inductance is a function of coil geometry and number of turns, and is independent of current.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Similar analysis applies to a solenoid with a magnetic core, but only if the length of the coil is much greater than the product of the relative permeability of the magnetic core and the diameter.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] That limits the simple analysis to low-permeability cores, or extremely long thin solenoids.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] The presence of a core can be taken into account in the above equations by replacing the magnetic constant *μ0* with *μ* or *μ0μr*, where *μ* represents permeability and *μr* relative permeability.
[src:solenoids-relays/solenoid] Note that since the permeability of ferromagnetic materials changes with applied magnetic flux, the inductance of a coil with a ferromagnetic core will generally vary with current.
